<DOC><DOCNO> AP890125-0095 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1031EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     01-25 0277</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Korea,0288</SECOND><HEAD>Roh Advised To Accept Opposition Demand For Referendum</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Government leaders today advisedPresident Roh Tae-woo to accept opposition demands for a referendumon whether voters support him, officials said.   At a meeting, leaders of the governing Democratic Justice Partytold Roh voters should have the chance to assess his performance,said party officials.   They said Roh called the meeting to deal with oppositionallegations he was trying to avoid the referendum.   On Tuesday, Kim Dae-jung and other opposition party leadersagreed to push for the referendum. Before he was elected in December1987, Roh promised he would hold such a referendum after takingoffice, but he set no date.   Government party leaders lack broad public support but have saidRoh is confident of victory.   Some opposition leaders contend Roh would have to resign if helost a referendum. Roh has only said he would ``acceptresponsibility'' if defeated.   Roh has introduced broad reforms since he took office inFebruary. But the opposition accuses him of being reluctant to takefirm action to deal with past government abuses.   Opposition leaders have demanded the government punish officialsinvolved in corruption and other abuses under the authoritariangovernment of former President Chun Doo-hwan.   Chun went into rural exile in November after making a publicapology for misdeeds under his administration, and Roh has asked thenation to pardon him.   In a related development today, prosecutors questioned three Chunloyalists, including the former government security head, ChangSe-dong, on charges of abusing power under the old government.   Chang played a key role in helping Chun seize power in a coup in1980.</TEXT></DOC>